\chapter{PTY Shell Sessions}
\label{tutorial-shell}

The central interaction problem is not menu rendering but shell control.
Students need a real shell so they can type normal commands, create
files, and inspect the workspace as they would in ordinary terminal use.

We therefore use a PTY-backed bash shell.  The PTY gives us two things a
plain subprocess does not: an interactive shell prompt and a transcript
that reflects what actually appeared in the terminal.


